From 578f34a63ba12b0d5c4996dd1a503bee83666755 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Chris Burr <christopher.burr@cern.ch>
Date: Sat, 17 Jan 2026 17:27:51 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 2/9] fix: Remove lowlink value from SCC error output for
 portability

The Tarjan SCC (Strongly Connected Components) algorithm uses a lowlink
value internally to track node visitation order during DFS traversal.
This value depends on the order in which graph nodes are iterated, which
in turn depends on the iteration order of unordered_map containers used
during graph construction (m_algoNameToAlgoNodeMap, etc.).

Since libstdc++ (GNU/Linux) and libc++ (macOS) have different hash map
iteration orders, the lowlink value differs between platforms even though
the SCC detection itself is correct (the same algorithms are identified
as belonging to the cycle).

The lowlink value is purely an internal implementation detail of Tarjan's
algorithm and provides no useful diagnostic information to users. The
important information is which algorithms form the cycle, not the
arbitrary numeric identifier assigned during traversal.

This change removes the lowlink value from the error output, making the
test results consistent across platforms while preserving all meaningful
diagnostic information.
